<br>
In 1988, I joined the army as a chemical operation specialist and went to training then to germany. <br>
<br>
Germany was probably the funnest time I have had in all of my life.  Basicly, I spent a huge amount of time enjoying europe and the offerings it had for a young soldier. <br>
<br>
In 1991, my unit got sent to Haf-Albatin Saudi arabia.  During the next 6 months. I sat in the desert. Saw a good friend killed by a truck accident. And generally messed up my health.  I left the army to enjoy my army college fund for a year and a half. <br>
<br>
In 1993, I rejoined the Army as a unassigned infantryman. And was trained to be a mechanized infantryman. About a month after getting to my unit at Ft. Steward, Ga. It was sent in response to a firefight in somalia. I arrived right at the end of what is now known as &quot;Blackhawk down&quot;.  I got a free trip to one of the worlds worst remains of a country that could possibly exist.  Nothing was left to really save in that country.  And for my time, I got to spend another 6 months sitting in a combat zone.  After which I came back to the states and served out another two and a half years. <br>
<br>
As my reenlistment time came up my unit was preparing to goto Serbia.  This wasn't expected to be a pleasure trip either.  They asked me if I wanted to reenlist. I can safely say, &quot;Three times to a combat zone isn't for me.&quot;<br>
<br>
I am glad I was not with my unit this year, 3/15th infantry second brigade spearheaded the movement to Bagdad and still sit at Bagdad international airport. <br>
<br>
<br>
In passing, I will say the following about the military.  It teaches discipline and good leadership principles. But, at the cost of possibly loosing your life.  As a member of the Army, you are very likely to go somewhere in the world. And the majority of the world doesn't like you.<br>
<br>
PoRelanex<br>
