<br>
Same thing enlisted.. but when you get in trouble as a private not much happens, noone expects you to be Superman.  It's different from an officer.  Also, if you were planning on making a career of it, you CAN enlist and then take the Warrant Officer path, although it takes awhile and there's a limit to the rank you can be promoted to.<br>
<br>
/agree Shintou on military health care.. set a mountain on fire in Pendleton and had to emergency hump out, broke my foot, then spent a month on crutches.. every other day it was malingering this and malingering that.. nevermind that an army officer at Redstone Arsenal gave me orders to stay off the thing for a month.<br>
<br>
Oh, and if you can play an instrument well, look into going into one of the service's band programs.. start off as an SNCO and it's supposed to be completely different than anything else..<br>
<br>
My last personal bit of advice.. if you do go in, make the most of it.  You can do alot of cool shit in the military that you won't get to do in the civilian world, so sign up for tours and B billets... alot of people may complain about being on a ship for 6 months out of a year, but I've a friend who did all 5 years of his enlistment at Camp Lejeune.. not a pretty sight <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=wiestrum>Wiestrum</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#A62A2A>(10/25/03 1:07 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2032.topic&index=33>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Military</span><hr size=1> I know if you go in with an associates, you go in as an E-3, get promoted to an E-4 within 6 months, and still can qualify for OCS. A bit of warning...If you go in as an officer, you are owned by the military. You can never enjoy your retirement, because at ANY time you can be called back to active duty.<br>
<br>
There was an E-5 in my Nat'l Guard unit, who was a pretty bright kid, but lazy as hell. Made E-5 in the active army, got out and took advantage of his G.I. bill. Got his B.S and went to OCS. He graduated top of his class, and the active Army tabbed him for a unit in Germany. He compalined that he was a Guard officer and they explained to him that he was An Army officer and we haven't seen him since. Yeah, the physical duties might be easier as an officer, but the responsibilities are far greater. Not much different as far as duty goes between the army and marines, both eat a lot of dirt, and I mean literally. Go Air Force! <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=741435&amp;resize=true">My Gear</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=bryannaesalvasti>Bryannae Salvasti</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I'm not a cleric!<br>
